<br>
To complicate things even further, my European friend characterizes Conservatives as &quot;Liberals&quot;, because in Europe the word &quot;liberal&quot; refers to Classical Liberalism, the core precepts of Western Liberal thought, namely:  every person deserves to live free, be treated equally by his/her gov't and by his/her community, to own and enjoy the fruits of his/her labor.  I am a conservative, but I certainly believe in those precepts.<br>
<br>
Those who we in America call &quot;liberals&quot; (who Reagan called liberals) are really socialists.  Why don't we call them that?  Well, that's another debate.<br>
<br>
No, I have an even more fundamental problem with the notion that there are two polar opposites:  right and left, as they are usually called.  I think that in most cases, people use these terms of convenience to pigeonhole their intellectal opponents, as in &quot;Oh, he's a leftist&quot;, or &quot;She's farther right than Atilla the Hun&quot; (as if!  as if Conservatives would support a marauding dictator!  Most dictators have been socialists, anyway: Mao, Stalin, Lenin, Hitler, Tito, Ceaucescu, Castro, just to name a few.  Those who are not socialists are by no means Conservatives in the American sense of the word).<br>
<br>
The emphasis we hear from our politicians today on right vs. left (or Republican vs. Democrats) has caused a marked and harmful partisan split in our people.  It's not a good thing.  There are many cases where we need to pull together as a nation (defense against terrorism is a prime example, boosting the economy is another).  It is not in our community interest to think of ourselves as being split into two sides, and then to grapple for control (so that, as Jonah Goldberg puts it, 51% of the population can pee in the cornflakes of the other 49%).<br>
<br>
But also, one can be Conservative and support legal abortion rights.  Or one can be Conservative and still support the legalization of drugs.  Or one can support civil rights and protection of civil liberties -- and still be a Conservative (sometimes this divergence is categorized as being &quot;socially liberal&quot; and &quot;fiscally conservative&quot;).<br>
<br>
So, although I accept the &quot;right vs. left&quot; labels as a kind of shorthand that lets us avoid long-winded explanations such as I have just written, I still think we would do better to keep an open mind and use more precise language that describes our feelings on each particular issue. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=therightguyatfcav>The Right Guy at FCAV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(12/27/03 10:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: &quot;right vs. left&quot; -- is this a helpful metaphor</span><hr size=1> Hi milkchaser,<br>
<br>
Right vs left has more to do with what side of the aisle our political leaders are on when in session. But over time it has become ideological in nature.<br>
<br>
I don't know if it's helpful to use this metaphor, but personally it seems a minor point. My personal feeling is this.... there is a struggle going on in our own country (and of course the world), and our president said it very clearly when he said it's a struggle between good and evil. This is not a ultra-right position I'm taking, it's just thinking through the situation we are in, and finding no better way to describe it.<br>
<br>
I firmly beleive in God and Country, and I beleive in the vast majority of issues that would be considered Conservative. Debating whether or not the Left vs Right metaphor is helpful seems to me to be a waste of time. We desperately need to get back to TRADITIONAL VALUES in this country, and we need to focus on this immediately.<br>
<br>
I'm in agreement that Conservatives can be a diverse group, but the basics stay the same. And I have no problem with the 2 party system. However, I wish the 2 parties would debate and discuss Conservative ideas instead of some of the Liberal/Socialist crap they waste time and money on.<br>
<br>
One last item... I am totally against legalizing drugs! Don't you think we have enough substance abuse in this country?<br>
<br>
David <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00000F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=milkchaser>milkchaser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(12/28/03 12:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: &quot;right vs. left&quot; -- is this a helpful metaphor</span><hr size=1> What a very interesting response.  I don't have time to write a response right now as we are about to embark on a family trip for the day, but I will. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fd10801>fd10801</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(12/29/03 12:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Left vs. Right</span><hr size=1> Maybe it's a good idea to see the &quot;center&quot; of the political spectrum as the top of a circle. Then, the extreme left and the extreme right meet at the &quot;bottom&quot; of the circle, where they resemble one another. Hence National(ist) Socialism [Nazism], all the way 'round' to the right, resembles (Soviet) Socialism) [Communism], all the way 'round' to the left, in its total control of society, which, of course, includes the economy.<br>
