<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I don't know if it's helpful to use this metaphor, but personally it seems a minor point....Debating whether or not the Left vs Right metaphor is helpful seems to me to be a waste of time. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
Well, thanks for reading what I had to say, nonetheless.  You may not think it is important, but let me say why I do.  I believe that a fundamental step before people can work together toward a goal is for them to understand the central ideas that they share.  <br>
<br>
I do not think labeling people as right or left is a useful way of viewing a complicated world, nor do I think it is an effective approach to persuading most people (as most people are well aware that life is more than a little complex and simple formulations don't usually pan out).  Moreover, if we want to work together, we cannot start by requiring that everybody conform to a particular view on all subjects.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>My personal feeling is this.... there is a struggle going on in our own country (and of course the world), and our president said it very clearly when he said it's a struggle between good and evil.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
However, I do not think the President was referring to either the right's struggle against the left, nor Republicans' struggle to solidify their control in Washington, nor to a struggle between traditional values vs. relativist thinking.  I think he was clearly and narrowly referring to the struggle of modern Democratic nations against terrorists and rogue nations.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I firmly beleive in God and Country, and I beleive in the vast majority of issues that would be considered Conservative.... We desperately need to get back to TRADITIONAL VALUES in this country, and we need to focus on this immediately.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This illustrates my point exactly.  I do not believe in God.  In fact, I believe there is no God.  Does this mean I cannot be a Conservative?  If you and I could potentially work together to keep babies from being aborted or to lower taxes, would you refuse because my &quot;values&quot; are not traditional?  If we both agree that the Federal Gov't is too big and too expensive, that free markets are better than protectionism, would you shun me because of the issues upon which we disagree?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm in agreement that Conservatives can be a diverse group, but the basics stay the same.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
And what would those basics be?  What are these &quot;traditional values&quot; that seem, to you, to be imperiled these days?  I am glad to see that you accept those who disagree with you and are willing to tolerate diversity of opinion.  So what are the core values that you think Conservatives believe?  I stated what I think they are in the second paragraph of my original post, here they are again:<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:blue;"><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>the core precepts of Western Liberal thought, namely: every person deserves to live free, be treated equally by his/her gov't and by his/her community, to own and enjoy the fruits of his/her labor.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>One last item... I am totally against legalizing drugs! Don't you think we have enough substance abuse in this country?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
A few points:<br>
1.  Drug prohibition has not stopped drug use.<br>
2.  Not all drug use is substance abuse, any more than all drinking is drunkenness.<br>
3.  Driving your car is riskier than smoking marijuana.  Driving your car over the speed limit is risky not only to you yourself, but to others as well.  In contrast, smoking marijuana is neglibly harmful and then only to the smoker, and yet, speeding will get you a traffic ticket and marijuana posession will get you a trip to jail.  This makes no sense.<br>
4.  There is nothing inherently wrong with intoxicating yourself.  Why is one form of intoxication considered evil while another, more dangerous form, is perfectly legal.<br>
5.  George Washington grew marijuana.  He even separated his male plants from the females, an indication that he was trying to increase the potency when smoked.<br>
6.  Our country was formed to preserve the right of the individual to live his life as he sees fit, not to enable those in the majority to use the State to impose their values upon the rest of the population.  There are a number of safeguards in the Federal Constitution, for example, that preserve minority rights (and here I do not mean racial minority).<br>
<br>
