Well, I will confess that your two-dimensional model of political thought is more helpful than the single-dimensioned &quot;right/left&quot; dichotomy.  Three of those political quizzes tried to graph political thought in two dimensions, and one of them just repeated the old, tired right vs. left model with politicians ranked from Jesse Jackson on the left through Kennedy, Hillary, Bill Clinton on the left to Ronald Reagan as the farthest to the right.<br>
<br>
Again, I just think these labels are neither accurate nor helpful because there are way more than even two dimensions.  I think we get ourselves in trouble when we start thinking of those Americans who either disagree with us on some issue or who belong to a different political party as our enemies somehow.<br>
<br>
Moreover, I think that there are unifying principles that justify a Conservative to be pro-choice on abortion, against drug prohibition, for more freedom for gays, while at the same time supporting free markets; smaller, less expensive and more responsive government; lower taxes; limited Federal gov't power (returning such power to the States and to the people), etc.  The world would not go to hell in a handbasket if we did our preaching from the pulpits and not from the well of the Congress.  If we want to bring about a more moral world, we should do it one person at a time, changing one heart at a time.  But it certainly cannot be done through legislation.<br>
<br>
You also state that there is a trade-off between liberty and equality.  I do not see how or why this is.  For example, let us suppose that we passed laws legalizing drugs and gay marriage.  I think this is the right thing, by the way, because Liberty is a core Conservative value.  If we granted these liberties to the minority of the population who choose to exercise them, how would this impact the equality of the rest of us?<br>
<br>
Now, it is true that our Constitution guarantees equal justice under the law and this has been construed, for example, to limit the freedom of the States to draw arbitrary borders for Congressional districts.  However, the right to vote and the freedom to voice one's opinion in those elections remains intact. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=milkchaser>milkchaser</A> at: 12/29/03 7:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=therightguyatfcav>The Right Guy at FCAV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(12/29/03 8:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: &quot;right vs. left&quot; -- is this a helpful metaphor</span><hr size=1> It is obvious that we have different ideas of what Conservativism is (please no Clinton joke about the word &quot;is&quot;).<br>
<br>
