What they want is treatment as &quot;next of kin&quot;; inclusion in medical plans, as 'spouses' or 'family'; and the right to be beneficiaries of salary protection plans, and other life insurance policies. Is this not a quest for &quot;equal treatment&quot;?<br>
Even the campaign for legalization of marijuana is an attempt to decriminalize the use of an obvious &quot;gateway&quot; drug, and at the same time, an attempt to remove the stigma of drug use from the people who use drugs. This, too, is an attempt at equality.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00000F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=milkchaser>milkchaser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/22/04 11:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Right vs. Left</span><hr size=1> I do not understand your point, because I think you are not making it very well -- perhaps not saying what you mean just yet.<br>
<br>
For instance, you tried to 'illustrate the &quot;trade-off&quot; between liberty and equality: legalizing gay marriage'.  However, your example shows how granting gays liberty to marriage would result in granting them equality as well.  That's not a trade-off.  Gays gain liberty and gain equality.<br>
<br>
A trade-off, on the other hand, is when I give up one thing in order to gain something else.  I give up talking to my wife over breakfast, but I gain the opportunity to advance a political discussion, for example (which is what I'm doing now).<br>
<br>
I suggest that liberty and equality are independent of each other.  You can advance liberty and increase equality at the same time.  For example, when women were given the right to vote, we increased their freedom (allowing them to enter the polling place, participate in elections, run for office or stay home as before -- do as they chose to do), but we also made them equal to male citizens.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>legalizing gay marriage results in affording gay unions the benefits of marriage<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
This is what logicians call a tautology.  It's like saying that Al Gore lost the election because he didn't win.<br>
<br>
I feel confident that you have a point, but what is it?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What [gays] want is treatment as &quot;next of kin&quot;; inclusion in medical plans, as 'spouses' or 'family'; and the right to be beneficiaries of salary protection plans, and other life insurance policies. Is this not a quest for &quot;equal treatment&quot;?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yes, and it also makes them more free.  Again, you have cited an instance where freedom and equality go hand in hand.  I hope you are open to my point that there is not always a trade-off between these two.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Even the campaign for legalization of marijuana is an attempt to decriminalize the use of an obvious &quot;gateway&quot; drug, and at the same time, an attempt to remove the stigma of drug use from the people who use drugs. This, too, is an attempt at equality.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
And here you seem to be going off-topic and the wheels really come off your argument.  Legalizing marijuana clearly increases freedom -- the freedom of marijuana smokers to do what they want (not a bad idea, given that it is not all that harmful -- if you were to try it you would see that for yourself).  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>And</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> legalizing pot would afford pot smokers equal treatment with tobacco smokers (which is much more likely a gateway drug) and alcohol drinkers (which is provably more lethal, and more dangerous to others considering that the effects of a drunk driver are incredibly worse than the effects of a potsmoking driver -- alcohol tends to reduce inhibitions and pot tends to increase them, thus drunks drive fast and sloppy and stoned drivers are slow and careful).<br>
<br>
So, legalizing pot would increase both liberty and equality.  This is not a trade-off.<br>
<br>
Now, I don't want to suggest that because you're wrong on the issue of liberty/equality trade-off, you are necessarily wrong on the pot legalization issue.  These are two different topics.  I like to keep them straight, even if you neglect to do so.<br>
<br>
I do think you are wrong on the pot legalization issue.  Since you think that pot is a gateway drug, I suspect you don't know much about pot.  It's a gateway to chocolate eating, I suppose, and potato chip consumption (pot tends to make its users hungry for carbohydrates).  But there is a strong or stronger correlation between past chocolate consumption and future heroin consumption than past pot consumption (ie. ~100% of heroin users are past chocolate users).  What does this prove?  Nothing.  The same goes for correlation between pot and heroin.  Many pot smokers have not, will not do heroin.  To suggest a connection is irrational.<br>
<br>
As for removing the stigma of drug use, this is only bad if there is something bad about using drugs.  If it turned out that smoking pot made you live longer (I'm purposely being absurd), then it would be wrong to maintain the stigma, right?<br>
<br>
In fact, most pot smokers are otherwise law abiding.  They would not be criminals if not for the prohibition of their favorite intoxicant.  If they smoke pot and do no harm to others, if you cannot even tell whether they use drugs without conducting chemical tests on their urine, then what possible ill effects can they be causing society?<br>
<br>
Listen, we conservatives are not given a blank check to be irrational.  We should still try to run the country with our brains and not our emotions. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000028><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=fd10801>fd10801</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/22/04 4:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Left vs. Right</span><hr size=1> I'm inclined to agree with you that I have not successfully demonstrated that an &quot;increase&quot; in liberty would lead to a &quot;decrease&quot; in equality, or vice versa.<br>
So I will leave the field, bloodied but unbowed, in that area.<br>
However, you couldn't be more wrong in assuming that I think marijuana is a gateway drug, and that I overestimate the damage it can do, because I've never tried it.<br>
Actually, although my personal life shouldn't enter into the argument, I'll tell you that I smoked pot almost every single day for twenty years. I also drank almost every kind of alcoholic beverage known to man, in over a dozen countries, and several dozen states.<br>
I've done nearly every kind of pain killer, barbituate, amphetamine derivative and hallucinogen.<br>
I've done cocaine in both the nasal and smokable forms.<br>
If I tell you marijuana is a gateway drug, it's because I <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>know</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> it to be so.<br>
It's so easy for people who are pro-legalization to say, &quot;You don't know anything about drugs, because you've never tried them,&quot; that they soon come to believe that it's a meaningful argument. It isn't. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#00000F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bfcavconservatives.showUserPublicProfile?gid=milkchaser>milkchaser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(1/22/04 4:54 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Left vs. Right</span><hr size=1> I'm sorry for assuming that you had never tried pot.  Still, how can you blame pot?  Pot didn't make you try all of those drugs.  Did it?  Did the reefer twist your arm?<br>
<br>
I do believe that our experience informs our beliefs.  It is ridiculous to assert otherwise.  However, we err when we try to extrapolate from our personal experience to others.<br>
<br>
Since you do have so much experience with various drugs, you should be in a good position to explain why pot needs to be illegal when alcohol and tobacco do not.  Most drinkers and smokers are responsible, as are most pot smokers.  Most do not become addicted, nor let these substances control their lives. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page  <b>1</b> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showMessageRange?topicID=13.topic&start=21&stop=21>2</a> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showPrevMessage?topicID=13.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showNextMessage?topicID=13.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=13.topic&index=20><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/black_default/addReply.gif border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.emailToFriend?topicID=13.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.threadControl?topicID=13.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/black_default/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands</a><br> <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=13.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/ultimate/subscribe.gif width=20 height=20 border=0 alt="Click to receive email notification of replies"> Click to receive email notification of replies</a> <br>  <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/ffcavconservativesfrm2.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=13.t